{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2731"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2731"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.35,0.52,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44816"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2731"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1280"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7903"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44093"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44816"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old baby girl is brought to see her General Practitioner by her mother for a rash that has developed around the infant\u0027s mouth. Her mother first noticed the rash two weeks ago and thinks it is becoming worse. Her daughter has never had this before and she has not tried any treatment for it. She does not think her daughter is bothered by the rash. The child is otherwise well. She is meeting all her developmental milestones, is growing as expected, has no other medical conditions or allergies that her mother is aware of, and is up to date on her immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is an erythematous rash in the peri-oral region that spreads down her chin as well. It is not well demarcated, there are no signs of infections and the rash blanches when pressure is applied. There is an abundance of saliva around her mouth and chin. There are no other rashes on her body. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atopic dermatitis","Irritant contact dermatitis","Peri-orificial dermatitis","Allergic contact dermatitis","Seborrhoeic dermatitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrritant contact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely condition affecting this young child. It is extremely common in young babies and is also called \u2018dribble rash\u2019. The irritant in this case is saliva that drools out of their mouth and spends prolonged amounts of time on their face around the mouth and chin area. The rash is confined to the area where the irritant touches the skin. The management includes reducing the irritant exposure, such as regularly removing drool from the baby\u2019s face, emollients, and barrier creams. Topical steroids may also be used to reduce the inflammation of the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtopic dermatitis \u003C/strong\u003Eor eczema is common in children. It has a similar appearance to the rash described, such as being not very well demarcated but it is generally itchy and affects areas of skin that are dry. Eczema commonly involves cheeks and perioral skin during infancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeri-orificial\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Edermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition that mainly affects adolescents and adults. The name is rather deceiving as this presents with discrete erythematous papular eruption around the perioral, peri-nasal or peri-ocular skin.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic contact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E describes an allergic reaction to a substance that was in contact with the skin. The rash is often well demarcated and limited to the region in contact with the allergen. Saliva is an irritant; it does not induce an allergic reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E (infantile) is another common condition that affects babies and toddlers, it is also called \u2018cradle cap\u2019. It is a form of eczema that affects the sebaceous glands of the scalp, face and trunk. In infants it causes a crusty, salmon pink rash that flakes and generally affects the scalp. This is not consistent with the rash described.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dribble rash in babies is a result of irritant contact dermatitis.","The two types of contact dermatitis include irritant and allergic.","Peri-oral dermatitis demonstrates sparing of the skin border around the lips."],"references":["Ngan V. Irritant contact dermatitis. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2003. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/irritant-contact-dermatitis/.","Oakley A. Periorifical dermatitis. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2016. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/periorificial-dermatitis/.","Oakley A. Sebborrhoeic dermatitis. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2017. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/seborrhoeic-dermatitis/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2731"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-01T19:22:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-01T19:22:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2731"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44816"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"}